      "id":"politics/2013/oct/17/labour-debate-security-service-watchdog-hazel-blears",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T20:30:35Z",
      "webTitle":"Senior Labour MP welcomes public debate over security service powers",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/17/labour-debate-security-service-watchdog-hazel-blears",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/17/labour-debate-security-service-watchdog-hazel-blears",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"2",
        "trailText":"Hazel Blears says watchdog will be more transparent and rebuffs Nick Clegg's call for review over accountability",
        "headline":"Senior Labour MP welcomes public debate over security service powers",
        "body":"<p>Hazel Blears, the senior Labour member of parliament's <a href=\"http://isc.independent.gov.uk/\" title=\"\">intelligence and security committee</a>, said  it was right that a debate was under way in Britain over the powers of the security services, adding that the inquiry into agencies' powerful new capabilities would go wherever the evidence takes it.</p><p>She also hit back at Nick Clegg for suggesting that there needed to be a review of the oversight of the security services, noting that the powers of the ISC had only just been enhanced.</p><p>Blears, a former cabinet minister with responsibility for counter-terrorism, was speaking the day after the ISC announced it was broadening its inquiry into the legal accountability of the services to include the balance between individual privacy and national security.</p><p>Her willingness to talk in public about the inquiry reflects a determination by the ISC to show greater openness about its work. The normally secretive committee, appointed by the prime minister, has tended to rely on statements from its chairman, Sir Malcolm Rifkind, and its sometimes redacted published reports.</p><p>Blears said: \"We are going to ask people to come and give us evidence on these issues, and provided we are not dealing with classified information, then we should be able to do that in public which I think would be very helpful. In the next week or so, I think we are going to be sending out invitations to a wide range of people. There are quite a lot of NGOs and thinktanks, but we want as wide a range of views as we can get. There is a public debate going on, rightly so. Some of what we do is in private because we are dealing with classified information, but if you can do it in public, that is a good thing.</p><p>\"We have had a furore in the past couple of weeks. Some of it has been pretty inaccurate, such as calling for a review of oversight when we have only just done that in the Justice and Security Act.\" Confirming she was referring to Clegg, she said: \"He sounded as if he was not aware of the provisions of the legislation which gives us extra powers to cross-examine witnesses and do a bigger oversight job. We have now got increased powers, we are getting increased resources. The committee is becoming a more powerful body and we will soon be having our first open session with the heads of the agencies. Those are all symbolic of us operating in a more open way as far as is commensurate with some of the stuff we have to examine.</p><p></p><p>\"At the end of the day, it comes down to: 'Have they got the right powers? Are there sufficient safeguards? Are they appropriate for the massive explosion in internet traffic and capabilities?' All of those are inextricably linked with the legal framework. That is what we are about. We are a body of oversight to ensure that the agencies are operating in compliance not just with the law, but with human rights. Increasingly the threat to our national security is migrating from mobile phone to voice-over internet, PlayStation games and all of that.\"</p><p>The ISC is expected to call for evidence as early as next week, but may not start to take oral evidence until the new year when it will have completed its inquiry into the Woolwich murder. Heads of the agencies are due to appear in front of the ISC next month.</p><p>Blears said she did not know if the inquiry would reach a view on whether the Guardian had \"endangered national security\", as alleged by David Cameron. She said: \"We will be taken where the evidence takes us. We will not have very strict limts on the terms of reference because we want to do a proper job.\"</p><p>Clegg again questioned the quality of the oversight of the agencies. Speaking on LBC, the deputy prime minister said: \"I think it is entirely legitimate to ask ourselves whether … the way in which we make sure the agencies, who by definition have to work in secret, do so in a way which is accountable. If you don't have proper accountability in a way that the public trusts and understands – because quite a lot of the accountability mechanisms we have got at the moment are very much kind of Westminster village stuff – the problem then is people start losing faith in the whole system.</p><p>\"Then of course there is the bigger issue, a debate which is happening here and on the other side of the Atlantic, which is just how these big, new, powerful technologies are used both by security agencies and indeed by people who wish to do us harm.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420300007|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|c56022c694f95100384ba3f06a23701463f996f3 -->",
